HEADWORD: Metic
<hw>Met"ic</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/,
prop., changing one's abode; <?/, indicating change + <?/ house, abode:
cf. L. <ets>metoecus</ets>, F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧t⟦egrave⟧que</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Gr. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A sojourner; an immigrant; an alien
resident in a Grecian city, but not a citizen.</def>
<rj><au>Mitford.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The whole force of Athens, <qex>metics</qex> as well as citizens,
and all the strangers who were then in the city.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett
(Thucyd. ).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>meticulosity</ent>⟦br⟧
